description.narrative:
This summary of SHAPE-SEA results covers the period July 2019 - December 2020.
As a response to the Covid-19 pandemic during 2020, SHAPE-SEA initiated an electronic op-ed series entitled "Southeast Asia in Crisis: Human Rights, Peace, Covid-19". The series includes nearly 150 short articles by different researchers, scholars, students as of December 2020. The goal of the initiative is to provide academics, students, researchers a platform to share their voices, reflections, expertise and/or analyses on various themes and realities related to the crisis. The articles are currently available from the SHAPE-SEA website: https://shapesea.com/op-ed-southeast-asia-in-crisis-opinions-on-the-state-of-human-rights-and-peace-in-the-time-of-covid-19/. 
SHAPE-SEA has published a number of new books, including:
- The Nexus of Technolgies and Human Rights: Opportunities and Challenges in Southeast Asia (2019);
- The Remapping and Analysis of Human Rights and Peace Education in ASEAN/SoutheastAsia (2019);
- Human Rights in Southeast Asia Outlook 2018 (2019);
- SEAHRN Human Rights and Peace in Southeast Asia Series 7 (2019);
- The Spectra of Authoritarianism in Southeast Asia (2019).
SHAPE-SEA's Education Committe developed a teaching module to support lecturers using the Human Rights in Southeast Asia Textbook.
Partly due to SHAPE-SEA outreach to ASEAN and its Member States, ASEAN adopted a proposal to include Human Rights and Peace Education in universities, and included the aim in the five year working plan of the ASEAN Intergovernmental Commission on Human Rights (2021-2025).
Since 2019 the Surabaya Principles of Academic Freedom, a result of SHAPE-SEA support, were being used as a standard for Academic Freedom in Indonesia.
